          "body": "Ibzan, Elon, and Abdon follow in seven verses. The narrator's terseness is deliberate. Ibzan is remembered for sixty children and strategic marriages — dynasty-building, not covenant-keeping (12:8-9). Elon receives ten years and nothing else (12:11-12). Abdon's seventy descendants riding seventy donkeys are the chapter's final image of worldly success: a judge measured by the number of animals his heirs could ride (12:13-14). The four-times-repeated death formula — 'he died and was buried' — is the chapter's quiet elegy. Hebrews 7:23 notes that the Levitical priests 'existed in greater numbers because they were prevented by death from continuing' — the same logic applies to the judges. The book of Judges is building, through its accumulation of deaths, toward the need for a judge who holds his office permanently because he lives forever. Chapter 12 presses that need with four consecutive graves."
