        "body": "The brevity of Jephthah's obituary — six years, died, buried in an unnamed city — is a studied contrast to the elaborate narrative of chapters 11-12:6. The man who negotiated with Ammon's king (11:12-28), made the rash vow (11:30-31), watched his only daughter walk to meet him (11:34), won the great victory (11:33), and slaughtered 42,000 of his own people (12:6) is dismissed in one sentence. The narrator neither condemns nor praises. He records and moves on.\n\nThe theological import of the unnamed burial city is debated. Barry Webb (*The Book of Judges*, NICOT) suggests the vagueness may reflect genuine historical uncertainty, while others argue it signals that Jephthah's legacy, unlike the patriarchs who were buried in specific, named, remembered places, has no lasting monument. Either way, the contrast with Ibzan (buried in Bethlehem), Elon (buried at Aijalon), and Abdon (buried at Pirathon) — all named cities — is striking. The judge who did the most receives the least memorial geography.\n\nHebrews 11:32 names Jephthah in the faith hall of fame alongside Gideon, Barak, and Samson — a company of profoundly flawed believers whose faith was real but whose lives were a long catalogue of costly mistakes. The New Testament commendation does not erase the Judges narrative; it confirms that God works through instruments whose moral record is mixed. Jephthah's six years are six years that Israel survived under external threat. Whether the covenant community was spiritually strengthened is another question entirely.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shaphat* (judged) is the book's defining verb for the deliverer-administrator role. Its use with a numeric tenure ('judged X years') always introduces or closes a minor judge's entry. Jephthah is the only major judge whose entry uses this formula — signaling that the Jephthah cycle (chapters 10-12) is formally closed and the reader is entering the minor judge succession list."
